<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-07-24T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-07-24T14:00:00-05:00" n="190" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d190">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/4755:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Vice Consul at Leopoldville</hi>
                                    (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Mallon</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-24T15:00:00-04:00">July
                                        24, 1940—3 p.m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <list>
                                <label>1.</label>
                                <item>Consulate at Lagos reports that according to captain of
                                    American steamship <hi rend="italic">Zarembo</hi> 2 British
                                    warships entered Pointe Noire and took over 2 French passenger
                                    vessels carrying 650 persons each, including American citizens.
                                    Please investigate and report, particularly as to whereabouts of
                                    American passengers.</item>
                                <label>2.</label>
                                <item>The Department would be glad to have an informal estimate of
                                    number of American citizens in Congo or nearby French colonies
                                    who might desire to return to the United States if
                                    transportation should be made available.</item>
                            </list>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>